WEBVTT

00:00:01.168 --> 00:00:04.520
How People with Disabilities
Use Digital Technology.

00:00:05.040 --> 00:00:09.920
Dhruv, older adult student who is deaf.

00:00:10.647 --> 00:00:18.280
Hello!
My name is D-H-R-U-V, Dhruv.

00:00:18.313 --> 00:00:20.823
I’m Deaf.

00:00:21.340 --> 00:00:26.261
I can hear some sounds

00:00:26.285 --> 00:00:30.247
but not enough to understand speech.

00:00:30.272 --> 00:00:35.188
I sign British Sign Language.

00:00:35.213 --> 00:00:40.335
I think and dream in signs.

00:00:40.360 --> 00:00:43.455
I recently enrolled in an online degree.

00:00:43.480 --> 00:00:46.843
For my classes I can schedule
interpreters who interpret

00:00:46.868 --> 00:00:50.468
the lectures and conversations,
and voice for me.

00:00:50.493 --> 00:00:54.055
I need video conferencing apps
with functionality to “pin” videos

00:00:54.080 --> 00:00:58.480
of the interpreters
so that I can always see them.

00:01:02.880 --> 00:01:07.231
Some lectures have realtime captioning
typed by human captioners.

00:01:07.256 --> 00:01:09.831
This is more accurate
than automatic captions,

00:01:09.856 --> 00:01:13.596
which often don’t recognize
specialized terms in the lectures.

00:01:13.621 --> 00:01:16.963
For our assigned videos,
I rely on good captions.

00:01:16.988 --> 00:01:20.163
These are edited so that each sentence
appearing on the screen

00:01:20.188 --> 00:01:24.073
is not too long
and is synchronized with the audio.

00:01:24.098 --> 00:01:27.364
I also often find myself
needing to adjust the text size

00:01:27.389 --> 00:01:31.173
and colors of the captions,
to be able to read them better.

00:01:31.198 --> 00:01:35.547
Some apps allow me to move the captions
to the top or bottom of the video,

00:01:35.572 --> 00:01:37.855
so that they are not in the way.

00:01:37.880 --> 00:01:41.563
In some situations,
I find myself lip reading.

00:01:41.588 --> 00:01:45.429
For example, when I’m on unplanned calls
without interpreters

00:01:45.454 --> 00:01:47.795
or other people who can sign.

00:01:47.820 --> 00:01:51.195
I learned lip reading over the years
because of such situations

00:01:51.220 --> 00:01:53.770
but it’s not always reliable for me.

00:01:53.795 --> 00:01:56.874
I need to see the person’s mouth,
have them speak clearly,

00:01:56.899 --> 00:02:00.280
and seeing their gestures also helps.
Yet it’s exhausting

00:02:00.280 --> 00:02:03.680
and not really something
I can keep doing for too long.

00:02:03.680 --> 00:02:05.920
I also use the chat function.

00:02:05.920 --> 00:02:10.640
Some chat tools support realtime text
rather than line-by-line text messages.

00:02:11.240 --> 00:02:14.880
This is much more interactive,
and I can engage with my friends

00:02:14.880 --> 00:02:18.149
in text conversations
as others do by voice.

00:02:18.760 --> 00:02:21.978
Of course, the classes also come
with a lot of reading.

00:02:22.003 --> 00:02:26.111
I’m fine with that, except when
the writing is unnecessarily complex

00:02:26.136 --> 00:02:29.056
and without structure
like lists and headings.

00:02:29.080 --> 00:02:33.394
People don’t realize that for me
reading text involves extra effort,

00:02:33.419 --> 00:02:36.175
because sign language
is my native language.

00:02:36.200 --> 00:02:39.500
So, like for everyone else,
clear and simple writing

00:02:39.525 --> 00:02:42.056
makes text easier to understand.

00:02:42.476 --> 00:02:48.024
You can help make technology
accessible to me.

00:02:49.191 --> 00:02:52.280
Accessibility: It’s about people.

00:02:52.756 --> 00:02:55.271
For more information
from the Web Accessibility Initiative

00:02:55.296 --> 00:02:58.416
on How People with Disabilities
Use Digital Technology,

00:02:58.440 --> 00:03:02.920
visit w3.org/WAI/people.